Docker for Continuous Integration â Running Integration Tests in Docker
Objectives
Design and deploy a multi-container application stack using Docker and Docker Compose, with a PostgreSQL database backend and a Node.js API layer
Author a suite of integration tests that validate cross-container communication, data persistence, and API correctness
Build a Jenkins CI pipeline that automatically builds images, runs the test suite inside containers, and publishes structured test results
Prerequisites
Comfort navigating and editing files on a Linux/Ubuntu command line
Conceptual understanding of how HTTP APIs and relational databases interact
Familiarity with what a CI/CD pipeline does at a high level (trigger, build, test, report)
Lab Environment
You will work on a dedicated AWS EC2 Ubuntu instance provided by Al Nafi. The instance has a base Ubuntu installation; you will install all required tools in Task 1.

Task 1: Install and Verify the Required Toolchain
Step 1.1 â Install Docker Engine, Docker Compose, Node.js, and Jenkins
Install Docker Engine from the official Docker apt repository, then install the Docker Compose plugin, Node.js 20.x from the NodeSource repository, and Jenkins from the official Jenkins Debian repository. After installation, add your user to the docker group so that Docker commands run without sudo, then start and enable both the Docker and Jenkins system services.

Official installation references if any URL below has changed:

Docker: https://docs.docker.com/engine/install/ubuntu/
Node.js: https://github.com/nodesource/distributions
Jenkins: https://www.jenkins.io/doc/book/installing/linux/
sudo apt-get update -y
sudo apt-get install -y ca-certificates curl gnupg lsb-release git

# Docker Engine
sudo install -m 0755 -d /etc/apt/keyrings
curl -fsSL https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu/gpg \
  | sudo gpg --dearmor -o /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg
sudo chmod a+r /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg

sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list <<'EOF'
deb [arch=amd64 signed-by=/etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg] https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu jammy stable
EOF

sudo apt-get update -y
sudo apt-get install -y docker-ce docker-ce-cli containerd.io docker-buildx-plugin docker-compose-plugin
sudo usermod -aG docker "$USER"
Troubleshoot this step:

You may see: E: Malformed entry 1 in list file /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list â this means a backslash or newline corrupted the file.
Run cat /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list and confirm it is a single unbroken line; delete and recreate with the heredoc above if it is not.
Official reference: https://docs.docker.com/engine/install/ubuntu/
# Node.js 20.x
curl -fsSL https://deb.nodesource.com/setup_20.x | sudo -E bash -
sudo apt-get install -y nodejs
Troubleshoot this step:

You may see: E: Package 'nodejs' has no installation candidate after running the setup script.
Run cat /etc/apt/sources.list.d/nodesource.list and confirm the suite matches your Ubuntu codename (jammy for 22.04); if the file is empty or missing, re-run the curl command above.
Official reference: https://github.com/nodesource/distributions#debian-and-ubuntu-based-distributions
# Jenkins
curl -fsSL https://pkg.jenkins.io/debian-stable/jenkins.io-2023.key \
  | sudo tee /usr/share/keyrings/jenkins-keyring.asc > /dev/null

sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/jenkins.list <<'EOF'
deb [signed-by=/usr/share/keyrings/jenkins-keyring.asc] https://pkg.jenkins.io/debian-stable binary/
EOF

sudo apt-get update -y
sudo apt-get install -y jenkins java-17-openjdk-amd64

sudo systemctl enable --now docker
sudo systemctl enable --now jenkins

# Allow Jenkins to run Docker commands
sudo usermod -aG docker jenkins
sudo systemctl restart jenkins
Troubleshoot this step:

You may see: error: no such file or directory: /usr/share/keyrings/jenkins-keyring.asc or Jenkins fails to start with Failed to start jenkins.service.
Confirm the key file exists with ls -lh /usr/share/keyrings/jenkins-keyring.asc; if missing, re-run the curl command above, then check Java is installed with java -version.
Official reference: https://www.jenkins.io/doc/book/installing/linux/#debianubuntu
