Task 2: Design and Deploy a Containerised Multi-Service Application with Integration Tests
Step 2.1 â Build a Multi-Container Application Stack
Design and implement a project containing three services orchestrated by Docker Compose: a PostgreSQL 15 database, a Node.js REST API that performs CRUD operations against that database, and a dedicated test runner container. The API must expose at minimum four HTTP endpoints: a health check, a database connectivity probe, a resource listing endpoint, and a resource creation endpoint. The database schema must be initialised automatically when the stack starts â no manual SQL steps are permitted. All inter-service credentials must be supplied exclusively through environment variables; no credentials may be hard-coded in source files.

Acceptance criteria:

Running docker compose up --build from the project root brings all three services to a healthy state within 120 seconds, verified by docker compose ps showing healthy for the database and API containers and running for the test runner.
curl http://localhost:3000/health returns HTTP 200 with a JSON body containing a status field equal to "healthy", and curl http://localhost:3000/db-status returns HTTP 200 with a JSON body containing a status field equal to "connected", both without any manual intervention after docker compose up.
Step 2.2 â Author and Execute a Passing Integration Test Suite
Design and implement an integration test suite that runs inside the dedicated test runner container and communicates with the API and database over the Docker Compose internal network. The suite must cover: API health, database connectivity, successful resource creation, retrieval of created resources, and rejection of a duplicate resource. Tests must wait for upstream services to be ready before executing â no fixed sleep delays are permitted. The suite must produce a JUnit-format XML report written to a host-mounted volume so results survive container removal.

Acceptance criteria:

Executing docker compose -f docker-compose.test.yml up --build --abort-on-container-exit exits with code 0 and the test runner container logs show all test cases passing with zero failures.
A JUnit XML file is present on the host at ./test-results/junit.xml after the run completes, contains at least five <testcase> elements, and has a failures="0" attribute on the root <testsuite> element, verifiable with grep 'failures="0"' test-results/junit.xml.
Task 3: Build and Validate a Jenkins CI Pipeline
Step 3.1 â Configure Jenkins and Create a Declarative Pipeline
Complete the Jenkins initial setup by navigating to http://<your-instance-public-ip>:8080, unlocking Jenkins with the password found at /var/jenkins_home/secrets/initialAdminPassword (or /var/lib/jenkins/secrets/initialAdminPassword depending on installation method), installing the suggested plugins plus the Docker Pipeline plugin, and creating an admin account. Then create a declarative Jenkinsfile in your project repository that defines the following named stages in order: Checkout, Build Images, Start Services, Run Integration Tests, Publish Results, and Cleanup. The Cleanup stage must run in a post { always { } } block so containers are removed even when tests fail. The pipeline must pass the Docker socket into the build environment so that Docker commands execute from within the Jenkins agent.

Acceptance criteria:

Triggering a build from the Jenkins UI completes all six named stages with green status indicators, and the Jenkins build log shows the string All integration tests passed (or the equivalent success summary from your chosen test framework) without any manual intervention after clicking Build Now.
The Cleanup stage removes all containers and volumes created during the build, verified by running docker ps -a and docker volume ls on the host immediately after the pipeline finishes and confirming no project-namespaced containers or volumes remain.
Step 3.2 â Enable Scheduled Execution and Confirm Artifact Archival
Extend the pipeline to run automatically on a cron schedule of every 15 minutes using a Jenkins triggers { cron(...) } block. Configure the pipeline to archive the JUnit XML report using the junit step so that Jenkins renders a test trend graph, and archive the container log files using archiveArtifacts. Confirm that two consecutive scheduled builds complete without manual intervention and that the test trend graph appears on the job page.

Acceptance criteria:

After saving the updated Jenkinsfile and waiting up to 30 minutes, at least two builds appear in the Jenkins build history with timestamps 15 minutes apart and both show a green result, confirming the cron trigger is active.
Each completed build's detail page shows a Test Result link that opens a report listing all test cases by name with zero failures, and an Archived Artifacts section containing both the JUnit XML file and at least one container log file.
Expected Outcomes
A fully automated Docker-based CI workflow exists in which a single git push or scheduled trigger causes Jenkins to build images, start a multi-container environment, execute integration tests inside that environment, publish structured results, and clean up all resources without human input.
The Jenkins job page displays a test trend graph that accumulates data across multiple builds, demonstrating that the pipeline is repeatable and that test history is preserved.
Conclusion
This lab required you to design every layer of a containerised CI system from scratch: the application, the test harness, the multi-service orchestration, and the pipeline automation. The deliberate absence of templates forces you to reason about service dependencies, network isolation, credential management, and artifact lifecycle â skills that transfer directly to production CI/CD environments. Extend this foundation by adding code coverage reporting, parallel test shards, or a Docker image vulnerability scan stage as your next challenge.

